, _jsxs(_components.p, {\n      children: [\"Tom piece was shortly followed by Joel Hooks' \", _jsx(_components.a, {\n        href: \"https://joelhooks.com/digital-garden\",\n        children: \"My blog is a digital garden, not a blog\"\n      }), \" in early 2019. \", _jsx(Footnote, {\n        idName: 5,\n        children: \"Disclaimer that Joel is a mentor, collaborator and friend, so my exposure to the idea comes from his early advocacy and enthusiasm for it.\"\n      }), \" Joel focused on the \", _jsx(_components.em, {\n        children: \"process\"\n      }), \" of digital gardening, emphasising the slow growth of ideas through writing, rewriting, editing, and revising thoughts in public. Instead of slapping Fully Formed Opinions up on the web and never changing them.\"]\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.p, {\n      children: [\"Joel also added Amy Hoy's \", _jsx(_components.a, {\n        href: \"https://stackingthebricks.com/how-blogs-broke-the-web/\",\n        children: \"How the Blog Broke the Web\"\n      }), \" post to the pile of influential ideas that led to our current gardening infatuation. While not specifically about gardening, Amy's piece gives us a lot of good historical context. In it, she explores the history of blogs over the last three decades, and pinpoints exactly when we all became fixated on publishing our thoughts in reverse chronological order (spoiler: around 2001 with the launch of \", _jsx(_components.a, {\n        href: \"https://www.movabletype.org/\",\n        children: \"Moveable Type\"\n      }), \").\"]\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.p, {\n      children: [\"Amy argues that Moveable Type didn't just launch us into the \\\"\", _jsx(_components.strong, {\n        children: \"Chronological Sort Era\"\n      }), \"\\\". It also killed the wild, diverse, hodge-podge personalisation of websites that characterised the early web. Instead of hand-coding your own layout and deciding exactly how to arrange the digital furniture, we began to enter the age of standardised layouts. Plug n' play templates that you drop content into became the norm. It became harder and more technically involved to edit the HTML \u0026 CSS yourself.\"]\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.blockquote, {\n      children: [\"\\n\", _jsx(_components.p, {\n        children: \"\\\"Suddenly people werent creating homepages or even web pages... they were writing web content in form fields and text areas inside a web page.\\\"\"\n      }), \"\\n\"]\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsx(_components.p, {\n      children: \"Many people have lamented the web's slow transition from unique homepages to a bland ocean of generic Wordpress themes. Digital gardening is part of the pushback against the limited range of vanilla web formats and layouts we now for granted.\"\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.p, {\n      children: [\"Over the course 2019 and early 2020, more and more people began riffing on the concept. Shaun Wang compiled the \", _jsx(_components.a, {\n        href: \"https://www.swyx.io/digital-garden-tos/\",\n        children: \"Digital Gardening Terms of Service\"\n      }), \". Anne-Laure Le Cunff published a popular guide to setting up \", _jsx(_components.a, {\n        href: \"https://nesslabs.com/digital-garden-set-up\",\n        children: \"No-code Digital Gardens\"\n      }), \". The IndieWeb community hosted a \", _jsx(_components.a, {\n        href: \"https://indieweb.org/2020/Pop-ups/GardenAndStream\",\n        children: \"pop-up session\"\n      }), \" to discuss the history of commonplace books, personal wikis, and memory palaces.\"]\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.p, {\n      children: [\"By late 2020 this whole concept had attracted enough attention for the MIT Tech Review to write \", _jsx(_components.a, {\n        href: \"https://www.technologyreview.com/2020/09/03/1007716/digital-gardens-let-you-cultivate-your-own-little-bit-of-the-internet/\",\n        children: \"a short piece\"\n      }), \" on it. Perhaps this is the watershed moment when a Twitter buzzword has \\\"made it.\\\"\"]\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsx(ImageFrame, {\n      width: \"1100px\",\n      src: \"https://res.cloudinary.com/dxj9qr5gj/image/upload/c_scale,f_auto,q_auto:best,w_1000/v1622719057/maggieappleton.com/notes/garden-history/mit-gardens_shrink_vpgbsl.png\",\n      showalt: true,\n      alt: \"A feature about digital gardening on MIT's tech review\"\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsx(_components.h3, {\n      id: \"digital-gardenings-fertile-soil\",\n      children: \"Digital Gardening's Fertile Soil\"\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsx(_components.p, {\n      children: \"What made our current historical moment the right time for digital gardening to take off?\"\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsx(_components.p, {\n      children: \"The timing coincided with a few complimentary ideas and communities rallying around personal knowledge systems, note-taking practices, and reimagining tools for blogging. The scene was ripe for new ideas around curating and sharing personal knowledge online.\"\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsx(_components.p, {\n      children: \"Many of the people who jumped on the early digital gardening bandwagon were part of communities like...\"\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.ul, {\n      children: [\"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.li, {\n        children: [\"The \", _jsx(_components.a, {\n          href: \"https://indieweb.org/\",\n          children: \"IndieWeb\"\n        }), \" collective  a group that has been championing independent web spaces outside the walled gardens of Instatwitbook for nearly a decade.\"]\n      }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.li, {\n        children: [\"Users of the note-taking app \", _jsx(_components.a, {\n          href: \"https://roamresearch.com/\",\n          children: \"Roam Research\"\n        }), \"  Roam pioneered new ways of interlinking content and strongly appeals to people trying to build sprawling knowledge graphs.\"]\n      }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.li, {\n        children: [\"Followers of Tiago Forte's \", _jsx(_components.a, {\n          href: \"https://www.buildingasecondbrain.com/\",\n          children: \"Building a Second Brain\"\n        }), \" course which popularised the idea of actively curating personal knowledge.\"]\n      }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.li, {\n        children: [\"People rallying around the \", _jsx(_components.a, {\n          href: \"https://www.swyx.io/learn-in-public/\",\n          children: \"Learn in Public\"\n        }), \" ethos that encourages continuously creating 'learning exhaust' in the form of notes and summaries.\"]\n      }), \"\\n\"]\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsx(_components.h3, {\n      id: \"developer-led-gardening\",\n      children: \"Developer-led Gardening\"\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsx(_components.p, {\n      children: \"Many of these early adopters were people who understood how to build websites  either professional developers or enthusiastic hobbyists. Any kind of novel experimentation with the web requires knowing a non-trivial amount of HTML, CSS, and JS. Not to mention all the surrounding infrastructure required actually to get a site live. Developers took to the idea because they already had the technical ability to jump in play around with what garden-esque websites might look like.\"\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.p, {\n      children: [\"The current state of web development helped here too. While it feels like we've been in a slow descent into a horrifyingly complex and bloated web development process, a number of recent tools have made it easier to get a fully customised website up and running. Services like \", _jsx(_components.a, {\n        href: \"https://www.netlify.com/\",\n        children: \"Netlify\"\n      }), \" and \", _jsx(_components.a, {\n        href: \"https://vercel.com/\",\n        children: \"Vercel\"\n      }), \" have taken the pain out of deployment. Static site generators like \", _jsx(_components.a, {\n        href: \"https://jekyllrb.com/\",\n        children: \"Jekyll\"\n      }), \", \", _jsx(_components.a, {\n        href: \"https://www.gatsbyjs.com/docs/\",\n        children: \"Gatsby\"\n      }), \", \", _jsx(_components.a, {\n        href: \"https://www.11ty.dev/\",\n        children: \"11ty\"\n      }), \" and \", _jsx(_components.a, {\n        href: \"https://nextjs.org/\",\n        children: \"Next\"\n      }), \" make it easier to build sophisticated websites that auto-generate pages, and take care of grunt work like optimising load time, images, and SEO. \", _jsx(Footnote, {\n        idName: 6,\n        children: \"Plenty of people will disagree that this explosion of JavaScript-stuffed rubbish is a net gain for the web. We all lament the loss of being able to upload pure HTML and CSS files via FTP. But those days are gone, and the only thing we can do now is slowly untangle our JavaScript spaghetti and package it up into more accessible build tools.\"\n      }), \" These services are trying to find a happy middle ground between tediously hand-coding solutions, and being trapped in the restrictions of Wordpress or Squarespace.\"]\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.p, {\n      children: [\"While developers were the first on the scene, plenty of writers, researchers, and note-taking enthusiasts have been drawn to the idea of digital gardening.\\nTo help folks without programming skills join in, there's been a surge in templates and platforms that allow people to build their own digital gardens without touching a ton of code. I've written an entire guide to \", _jsx(InternalTooltipLink, {\n        title: \"Digital Gardening for Non-Technical Folks\",\n        description: \"How to build a digital garden without touching code\",\n        href: \"/nontechnical-gardening\",\n        children: \"Digital Gardening for Non-Technical Folks\"\n      }), \" if you fall into that category.\"]\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.p, {\n      children: [\"Tools like \", _jsx(_components.a, {\n        href: \"https://obsidian.md/\",\n        children: \"Obsidian\"\n      }), \", \", _jsx(_components.a, {\n        href: \"https://tiddlywiki.com/\",\n        children: \"TiddlyWiki\"\n      }), \", and \", _jsx(_components.a, {\n        href: \"https://www.notion.so/\",\n        children: \"Notion\"\n      }), \" are all great options. Many of them offer fancy features like nested folders, \", _jsx(InternalTooltipLink, {\n        title: \"A Short History of Bi-Directional Links\",\n        description: \"Seventy years ago we dreamed up links that would allow us to create two-way, contextual conversations. Why don't we use them on the web?\",\n        href: \"/bidirectionals\",\n        children: \"Bi-Directional Links\"\n      }), \", footnotes, and visual graphs.\"]\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.p, {\n      children: [\"However, many of these no-code tools still feel like cookie-cutter solutions. Rather than allowing people to design the \", _jsx(_components.a, {\n        href: \"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Information_architecture\",\n        children: \"information architecture\"\n      }), \" and spatial layouts of their gardens, they inevitably force people into pre-made arrangements. This doesn't meant they don't \\\"count, as \\\"real gardens, but simply that they limit their gardeners to some extent. You can't design different types of links, novel features, experimental layouts, or custom architecture. They're pre-fab houses instead of raw building materials.\"]\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsx(_components.hr, {}), \"\\n\", _jsx(_components.h2, {\n      id: \"the-six-patterns-of-gardening\",\n      children: \"The Six Patterns of Gardening\"\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsx(_components.p, {\n      children: \"In all the recent gardening flurry, we've run into the inevitable confusion around how to define the term.\"\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsx(TweetEmbed, {\n      tweetId: \"1260368292851535879\"\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.p, {\n      children: [\"There are contested ideas about what qualifies as a garden, what the core ethos should focus on, and whether it's worthy of a new label at all. What exactly makes a website a \", _jsx(_components.em, {\n        children: \"digital garden\"\n      }), \" as opposed to just another blog?\"]\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.p, {\n      children: [\"After reading all the existing takes on the term, observing a wide variety of gardens, and collecting some of the \", _jsx(_components.a, {\n        href: \"https://github.com/MaggieAppleton/digital-gardeners\",\n        children: \"best examples\"\n      }), \", I've identified a few key qualities they all share.\"]\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.p, {\n      children: [\"There are a few guiding principles, design patterns and structures people are rallying around. This amounts to a kind of digital gardening \", _jsx(InternalTooltipLink, {\n        title: \"Pattern Languages in Programming and Interface Design\",\n        description: \"Notes on pattern languages and Christopher Alexander's legacy on software programming\",\n        href: \"/pattern-languages\",\n        children: \"Pattern Language\"\n      }), \".\"]\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsx(Spacer, {\n      size: \"small\"\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsx(_components.h3, {\n      id: \"1-topography-over-timelines\",\n      children: \"1. Topography over Timelines\"\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.p, {\n      children: [\"Gardens are organised around \", _jsx(_components.strong, {\n        children: \"contextual relationships and associative links\"\n      }), \"; the concepts and themes within each note determine how it's connected to others.\"]\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsx(_components.p, {\n      children: \"This runs counter to the time-based structure of traditional blogs: posts presented in reverse chronological order based on publication date.\"\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsx(_components.p, {\n      children: \"Gardens don't consider publication dates the most important detail of a piece of writing. Dates might be included on posts, but they aren't the structural basis of how you navigate around the garden. Posts are connected to other by posts through related themes, topics, and shared context.\"\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.p, {\n      children: [\"One of the best ways to do this is through \", _jsx(InternalTooltipLink, {\n        title: \"A Short History of Bi-Directional Links\",\n        description: \"Seventy years ago we dreamed up links that would allow us to create two-way, contextual conversations. Why don't we use them on the web?\",\n        href: \"/bidirectionals\",\n        children: \"Bi-Directional Links\"\n      }), \"  links that make both the destination page and the source page visible to the reader. This makes it easy to move between related content.\"]\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsx(BasicImage, {\n      width: \"900px\",\n      alt: \"A linear timeline of posts vs. a spatial layout of connected posts\",\n      src: \"https://res.cloudinary.com/dxj9qr5gj/image/upload/c_scale,f_auto,q_auto:best,w_1100/v1621774501/maggieappleton.com/notes/garden-history/topographytimelines_shrink_jxgw9l.png\"\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsx(_components.p, {\n      children: \"Because garden notes are densely linked, a garden explorer can enter at any location and follow any trail they link through the content, rather than being dumped into a \\\"most recent feed.\"\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.p, {\n      children: [\"Dense links are essential, but gardeners often layer on other ways of exploring their knowledge base. They might have \", _jsx(_components.a, {\n        href: \"https://busterbenson.com/piles/\",\n        children: \"thematic piles\"\n      }), \", \", _jsx(_components.a, {\n        href: \"https://tomcritchlow.com/wiki/\",\n        children: \"nested folders\"\n      }), \", tags and filtering functionality, \", _jsx(_components.a, {\n        href: \"https://www.christopherbiscardi.com/garden\",\n        children: \"advanced search bars\"\n      }), \", \", _jsx(_components.a, {\n        href: \"https://wiki.nikitavoloboev.xyz/\",\n        children: \"visual node graphs\"\n      }), \", or \", _jsx(_components.a, {\n        href: \"https://www.gwern.net/index\",\n        children: \"central indexes\"\n      }), \" listing notable and popular content.\"]\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsx(_components.p, {\n      children: \"Many entry points but no prescribed pathways.\"\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsx(Spacer, {}), \"\\n\", _jsx(_components.h3, {\n      id: \"2-continuous-growth\",\n      children: \"2. Continuous Growth\"\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.p, {\n      children: [\"Gardens are never finished, they're \", _jsx(_components.strong, {\n        children: \"constantly growing, evolving, and changing\"\n      }), \". Just like a real soil, carrot, and cabbage garden.\"]\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.p, {\n      children: [\"The isn't how we usually think about writing on the web. Over the last decade, we've moved away from casual live journal entries and formalised our writing into \", _jsx(_components.em, {\n        children: \"articles\"\n      }), \" and \", _jsx(_components.em, {\n        children: \"essays\"\n      }), \". These are carefully crafted, edited, revised, and published with a timestamp. When it's done, it's done. We act like tiny magazines, sending our writing off to the printer.\"]\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.p, {\n      children: [\"This is odd considering editability is one of the main selling points of the web. Gardens lean into this  there is no \\\"final version on a garden. What you publish is always open to revision and expansion. \", _jsx(Footnote, {\n        idName: 7,\n        children: \"Or more likely, contraction and clarification\"\n      })]\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsx(_components.p, {\n      children: \"Gardens are designed to evolve alongside your thoughts. When you first have an idea, it's fuzzy and unrefined. You might notice a pattern in your corner of the world, but need to collect evidence, consider counter-arguments, spot similar trends, and research who else has thunk such thoughts before you. In short, you need to do your homework and critically think about it over time.\"\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsx(BasicImage, {\n      width: \"950px\",\n      src: \"https://res.cloudinary.com/dxj9qr5gj/image/upload/c_scale,f_auto,q_auto:best,w_1000/v1621773885/maggieappleton.com/notes/garden-history/gardentime_rrsecv.png\",\n      alt: \"A graph of time versus amount of work. Gardening involves small amounts of work over time, while classic blogging involves a lot of work all at once.\"\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsx(_components.p, {\n      children: \"In performance-blog-land you do that thinking and researching privately, then shove it out at the final moment. A grand flourish that hides the process.\"\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsx(_components.p, {\n      children: \"In garden-land, that process of researching and refining happens on the open internet. You post ideas while they're still \\\"seedlings, and tend them regularly until they're fully grown, respectable opinions.\"\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsx(_components.p, {\n      children: \"This has a number of benefits:\"\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.ul, {\n      children: [\"\\n\", _jsx(_components.li, {\n        children: \"You're freed from the pressure to get everything right immediately. You can test ideas, get feedback, and revise your opinions like a good internet citizen.\"\n      }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.li, {\n        children: [\"It's \", _jsx(_components.em, {\n          children: \"low friction\"\n        }), \". Gardening your thoughts becomes a daily ritual that only takes a small amount of effort. Over time, big things grow.\"]\n      }), \"\\n\", _jsx(_components.li, {\n        children: \"It gives readers an insight into your writing and thinking process. They come to realise you are not a magical idea machine banging out perfectly formed thoughts, but instead an equally mediocre human doing The Work of trying to understand the world and make sense of it alongside you.\"\n      }), \"\\n\"]\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.p, {\n      children: [\"This all comes with an important caveat; \", _jsx(_components.strong, {\n        children: \"gardens make their imperfection known to readers\"\n      }), \". Which brings us to the next pattern...\"]\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsx(Spacer, {}), \"\\n\", _jsx(_components.h3, {\n      id: \"3-imperfection--learning-in-public\",\n      children: \"3. Imperfection \u0026 Learning in Public\"\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.p, {\n      children: [\"Gardens are \", _jsx(_components.strong, {\n        children: \"imperfect by design\"\n      }), \". They don't hide their rough edges or claim to be a permanent source of truth.\"]\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.p, {\n      children: [\"Putting anything imperfect and half-written on an \\\"official website may feel strange. \", _jsx(Footnote, {\n        idName: 8,\n        children: \"We seem to reserve all our imperfect declarations and poorly-worded announcements for platforms that other people own and control.\"\n      }), \" We have all been trained to behave like tiny, performative corporations when it comes to presenting ourselves in digital space. Blogging evolved in the \", _jsx(_components.a, {\n        href: \"https://www.ribbonfarm.com/2017/08/17/the-premium-mediocre-life-of-maya-millennial/\",\n        children: \"Premium Mediocre\"\n      }), \" culture of Millenialism as a way to Promote Your Personal Brand and market your SEO-optimized Content.\"]\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsx(_components.p, {\n      children: \"Weird, quirky personal blogs of the early 2000's turned into cleanly crafted brands with publishing strategies and media campaigns. Everyone now has a modern minimalist logo and an LLC.\"\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.p, {\n      children: [\"Digital gardening is the \", _jsx(_components.a, {\n        href: \"https://www.ribbonfarm.com/series/domestic-cozy/\",\n        children: \"Domestic Cozy\"\n      }), \" response to the professional personal blog; it's both intimate and public, weird and welcoming. It's less performative than a blog, but more intentional and thoughtful than a Twitter feed. It wants to build personal knowledge over time, rather than engage in banter and quippy conversations.\"]\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.p, {\n      children: [\"Think of it as a spectrum. Things we dump into private WhatsApp group chats, DMs, and cavalier Tweet threads are part of our \", _jsx(_components.em, {\n        children: \"chaos streams\"\n      }), \" - a continuous flow of high noise / low signal ideas. On the other end we have highly performative and cultivated artefacts like published books that you prune and tend for years.\"]\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsx(_components.p, {\n      children: \"Gardening sits in the middle. It's the perfect balance of chaos and cultivation.\"\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsx(BasicImage, {\n      width: \"1000px\",\n      alt: \"a spectrum of knowledge management, ranging from chaos streams to the cultivated performance of publishing a book. Gardening sits in the middle.\",\n      src: \"https://res.cloudinary.com/dg3gyk0gu/image/upload/c_scale,f_auto,q_auto:good,w_1100/v1593765637/maggieappleton.com/notes/garden-history/digital-garden.png\"\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.p, {\n      children: [\"This ethos of imperfection opens up a world of possibility that performative blogging shut down. First, it enables you to \", _jsx(_components.a, {\n        href: \"https://www.swyx.io/learn-in-public/\",\n        children: \"Learn in Public\"\n      }), \"; the practice of sharing what you learn as you're learning it, not a decade later once you're an \\\"expert. \", _jsx(Footnote, {\n        idName: 9,\n        children: \"A label you may never officially earn unless you're in a highly structured and bureaucratised industry that loves explicit hierarchy rankings. The rest of us are left to deal with perpetual imposter syndrome.\"\n      })]\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.p, {\n      children: [\"This freedom of course comes with great responsibility. Publishing imperfect and early ideas \", _jsx(_components.strong, {\n        children: \"requires that we make the status of our notes clear to readers.\"\n      }), \" You should include some indicator of how \\\"done they are, and how much effort you've invested in them.\"]\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsx(_components.p, {\n      children: \"This could be with a simple categorisation system. I personally use an overly horticultural metaphor:\"\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.ul, {\n      children: [\"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.li, {\n        children: [\" \", _jsx(_components.em, {\n          children: \"Seedlings\"\n        }), \" for very rough and early ideas\"]\n      }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.li, {\n        children: [\" \", _jsx(_components.em, {\n          children: \"Budding\"\n        }), \" for work I've cleaned up and clarified\"]\n      }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.li, {\n        children: [\" \", _jsx(_components.em, {\n          children: \"Evergreen\"\n        }), \" for work that is reasonably complete (though I still tend these over time).\"]\n      }), \"\\n\"]\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.p, {\n      children: [\"I also include the dates I \", _jsx(_components.em, {\n        children: \"planted\"\n      }), \" and \", _jsx(_components.em, {\n        children: \"last tended\"\n      }), \" a post so people get a sense of how long I've been growing it.\"]\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsx(ImageFrame, {\n      width: \"900px\",\n      src: \"https://res.cloudinary.com/dxj9qr5gj/image/upload/c_scale,f_auto,q_auto:good,w_1200/v1621931871/maggieappleton.com/notes/garden-history/metadata_jtz6od.png\",\n      alt: \"The metadata at the top of my posts showing growth stage\"\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.p, {\n      children: [\"Other gardeners include an \", _jsx(_components.strong, {\n        children: \"epistemic status\"\n      }), \" on their posts  a short statement that makes clear how they know what they know, and how much time they've invested in researching it.\"]\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.p, {\n      children: [_jsx(_components.a, {\n        href: \"https://www.gwern.net/index\",\n        children: \"Gwern.net\"\n      }), \" was one of the earliest and most consistent gardeners to offer meta-reflections on their work.\\nEach entry comes with:\"]\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.ul, {\n      children: [\"\\n\", _jsx(_components.li, {\n        children: \"topic tags\"\n      }), \"\\n\", _jsx(_components.li, {\n        children: \"start and end date\"\n      }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.li, {\n        children: [\"a stage tag: \", _jsx(_components.em, {\n          children: \"draft\"\n        }), \", \", _jsx(_components.em, {\n          children: \"in progress\"\n        }), \", or \", _jsx(_components.em, {\n          children: \"finished\"\n        })]\n      }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.li, {\n        children: [\"a certainty tag: \", _jsx(_components.em, {\n          children: \"impossible\"\n        }), \", \", _jsx(_components.em, {\n          children: \"unlikely\"\n        }), \", \", _jsx(_components.em, {\n          children: \"certain\"\n        }), \", etc.\"]\n      }), \"\\n\", _jsx(_components.li, {\n        children: \"1-10 importance tag\"\n      }), \"\\n\"]\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsxs(_components.p, {\n      children: [\"These are all explained in their \", _jsx(_components.a, {\n        href: \"https://www.gwern.net/About#confidence-tags\",\n        children: \"website guide\"\n      }), \", which is worth reading if you're designing your own epistemological system.\"]\n    }), \"\\n\", _jsx(ImageFrame, {\n      width: \"900px\",\n      src: \"https://res.cloudinary.com/dxj9qr5gj/image/upload/c_scale,f_auto,q_auto:good,w_1100/v1621499882/maggieappleton.com/notes/garden-history/Screenshot_-_2021-05-20_09.35.37_shrink_x79dnz.